In Thymeleaf 3.1.0+ you can provide the servlet path like this

```GlobalController.java```:
````java
@ControllerAdvice
public class GlobalController {

    @ModelAttribute(&quot;servletPath&quot;)
    String getRequestServletPath(HttpServletRequest request) {
        return request.getServletPath();
    }
}
````

And then you can use ${servletPath} in your html file:

Example ```navbar.html```:
````html
&lt;ul class=&quot;nav nav-pills&quot;&gt;
    &lt;li class=&quot;nav-item&quot;&gt;
        &lt;a class=&quot;nav-link&quot; th:classappend=&quot;${servletPath == &#39;/&#39; ? &#39;active&#39;:&#39;&#39;}&quot; href=&quot;/&quot;&gt;Home&lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;/li&gt;
    &lt;li class=&quot;nav-item&quot;&gt;
        &lt;a class=&quot;nav-link&quot; th:classappend=&quot;${servletPath == &#39;/parties&#39; ? &#39;active&#39;:&#39;&#39;}&quot; href=&quot;/csv&quot;&gt;Parties&lt;/a&gt;
    &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
````

----------
Additional:
If you don&#39;t want to pass servletPath to all your endpoints, you need to pass it manually on all endpoints for the pages used in the navigation:

````java
// Endpoint for thymeleaf. Add the ServletPath
@GetMapping(&quot;/parties&quot;)
public String getPartiesPage(Model model, HttpServletRequest request) {
    model.addAttribute(&quot;servletPath&quot;, request.getServletPath());
    return &quot;parties&quot;;
}

// Endpoint for other application. Don&#39;t add servletPath
@GetMapping(value = &quot;/v1/parties/{id}&quot;, produces = &quot;application/json;charset=utf-8&quot;)
public @ResponseBody PartyDto findBySystemOfRecordId(@PathVariable String id) {
    return partyService.findBySystemOfRecordId(id);
}
````

